    <li><strong>Value for size:</strong> Typically lower prices than comparable white diamonds.</li>
    <li><strong>Versatile styling:</strong> Works with minimalist, art-deco/vintage, pavé halo, or men’s bands.</li>
    <li><strong>Contrast play:</strong> White diamond halos or bright metals amplify the drama.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Cons</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Less “sparkle”:</strong> Opaque stones don’t show traditional fire or scintillation.</li>
    <li><strong>Inclusion-heavy:</strong> Many stones (especially treated) benefit from secure settings; avoid thin, exposed prongs.</li>
    <li><strong>Service nuance:</strong> At-home ultrasonic/steam cleaning isn’t advised for treated stones.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Black Diamond vs White Diamond</h2>
  <p>
    If your priority is classic brilliance and fire, a white diamond remains unbeatable. If you want bold presence and a fashion-forward statement, the black diamond wins. In many size ranges, you’ll also find black diamonds are more budget-friendly. Many clients choose a hybrid look — a black diamond center with a white diamond halo — to capture both contrast and sparkle.
  </p>

